Result

Model Specification

\(h_{ij}(t)\): Hazard at time t for Subject j in Center i.

\(h_{0}(t)\): Baseline hazard at time t.

\(\beta_1\): Fixed main effect of age.

\(\beta_2\): Fixed main effect of treatment.

\(\beta_3\): Interaction effect of age and treatment.

\(Treatment_{ij}\): Indicator that Subject j with center i, equalling 1, when treatment is Distal pancreatectomy or 0 when treatment is Whipple procedure.

\(b_i \sim N(0,\sigma_b^2)\). Random effect of Center i.

Model without interaction: \(h_{ij}(t)=h_0(t)exp(\beta_1Age_{ij}+\beta_2Treatment_{ij}+b_i)\)

Model with interaction: \(h_{ij}(t)=h_0(t)exp(\beta_1Age_{ij}+\beta_2Treatment_{ij}+\beta_3Age_{ij}Treatment_{ij}+b_i)\)

From anova test, we can see that the two models are not significant different with p=0.75, so we can use the simpler model. From the summary part, we can see that the coefficient of the interaction of age and treatment is -0.015, which is near 0, so we can use the model without interaction to estimate the relationship between progression and other variables.

Mixed Effect Cox-Regression without interaction:

There is no statistically signifiant associate between progression and other variables.

Model

GLMM Model without interaction

dat2$AppIn<-factor(dat2$AppIn,levels = c("Yes","No"),labels = c(1,0))

Result

Model Specification

\(p_{ij}\): Probability of response for Subject i with appetite increase j.

\(b_i \sim N(0,\sigma_b^2)\). Random effect of subject i.

\(\beta_1\): Fixed main effect of sleep.

\(\beta_2\): Fixed main effect of BMI.

\(\beta_3\): Interaction effect of sleep status and BMI.

\(1_{ij}\): Indicator that Subject i with appetite increase j had late sleep.

Model without interaction(GLMM): \(logit(p_{ij})=\alpha+b_i+\beta_11_{ij}+\beta_2BMI_{ij}\)

Model with interaction(GLMM): \(logit(p_{ij})=\alpha+b_i+\beta_11_{ij}+\beta_2BMI_{ij}+\beta_31_{ij}BMI_{ij}\)

Model without random effect(GLM): \(logit(p_{ij})=\alpha+\beta_11_{ij}+\beta_2BMI_{ij}\)

Using ANOVA to compare model without interaction and model without random effect. From the result, with p = 1, we can conclude that there is no significant difference between these models, so I choose the model without random effect due to smaller AIC and BIC.

Generalized linear model(Poisson regression):

There is no statistically significant sleep effect on appetite increase as noted by the estimate and p value (est=-1.03709; p=0.223) and there is no statistically significant BMI effect on appetite increase as noted by the estimate and p value (est=0.06921; p=0.685)
